                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>To the Rev. S. Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>Whilst words of burning eloquence<lb/> are inciting to patriotic warlike deeds<lb/> turn me to those teaching glory to God<lb/> and good will to one fellow&#45;man.<lb/></p>
            <p>You permit me Rev. Sir the<lb/> privilege of a frank expression of<lb/> opinion relative to your version of<lb/> &#34;Jacobs prophetic blessing&#34; A review<lb/> would require the time and ability<lb/> that I have not&#44; I hope however to<lb/> have the benefit of your counsel for<lb/> that which I do not comprehend&#59;<lb/> your view of &#34;the <sic>discrepencies</sic>&#34;<lb/> arising from various translations is<lb/> entirely new to me&#59; the privilege<lb/> assumed by Onkelos you approve&#44;<lb/> and therefore disseminate&#59; <sic>haply</sic> in<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>this instance it may be well&#44; but it is<lb/> so replete with consequences&#44; as perhaps<lb/> with danger that the Bomb intended<lb/> to crush an enemy might perchance de&#45;<lb/>&#45;stroy a friend.<lb/></p>
            <p>The version relative<lb/> to Reuben and Joseph strikes me as<lb/> admirable&#44; the preference so early shown<lb/> by the Father and the subsequent filial<lb/> conduct of Joseph renders it alike natural<lb/> and proper.<lb/></p>
            <p>Nothing can be more satisfac<lb/>&#45;tory too&#44; than that respecting Judah &#40;if<lb/> it can be borne out&#41; but of the last<lb/> sentence do I misunderstand&#44; or does<lb/> it limit &#34;the reign of Peace&#34; which we<lb/> have supposed would be unending.<lb/></p>
            <p>Take the Paraphrase as a whole it<lb/> strikes me as consonant with all the<lb/> views and wishes of the People whose<lb/> mission it is to propagate Truth<lb/> and who hope that when fulfilled<lb/> a blessing shall go forth from Zion<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>for so the Lord of Hosh hath<lb/> spoken.<lb/></p>
            <p>Of your exordium of the<lb/> prayer it scarce needs to say that words<lb/> of harmony&#44; pure thought and piety<lb/> characterize them&#44; may the first<lb/> find acceptance with our brethren<lb/> so that they may seek instruction where<lb/> it can be found&#44; and of the latter<lb/> with our God so that His wrath<lb/> may indeed be stayed&#44; His mercy<lb/> granted to His People now and<lb/> evermore.<lb/></p>
            <p>I trust we shall see the Discourse<lb/> in print&#44; so that others as well as our<lb/> own congregation may benefit by it&#44;<lb/> its very novelty will incite the scrawling<lb/> that happily our blessed tenets can bear<lb/> may you Sir be permitted to witness<lb/> happy results from your teaching is the<lb/> very sincere wish of yours with esteem<lb/> L. B. Hart<lb/></p>
            </body>
